'''David Griffiths''' (born 1950, [[Auckland, New Zealand]]) is a composer, baritone and convener of the ''Conservatorium of Music'' at the [[University of Waikato]]. Griffiths has gained national and international recognition as a [[composer]], [[opera singer]] and [[recital]] soloist.  His [[choral]] compositions are particularly popular in the [[United States of America]] and have, in recent years, been recorded by several choirs while many works have been included on various record labels including [[Naxos Records]], Kiwi Pacific and Atoll.

Griffiths has performed as a [[Solo (music)|soloist]] with the [[New Zealand Symphony Orchestra]], [[Auckland Philharmonia Orchestra]], all major choral societies in New Zealand and regularly with NBR [[New Zealand Opera]]. He has also performed as a recital soloist, representing New Zealand in [[Taiwan]], the [[USA]], the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Europe]].

Griffiths works as a freelance composer and is fully represented by SouNZ Aotearoa, the Center for New Zealand Music.  He has held positions of lecturer and senior lecturer in voice at universities throughout New Zealand and as such has trained singers who have gone on to perform with distinguished companies such as the [[Cologne Opera]] and The Bayreuth Chorus.

==Biography==
David Griffiths was born 1950 in [[Auckland]], and completed his schooling at Westlake Boys High School. He graduated in 1971 from the [[University of Auckland]] with a [[Bachelor of Music]] and studied composition at the [[Guildhall School of Music]] in [[London]] in 1972. Griffiths was awarded a [[Master of Music]] degree (1st class honors) in composition in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|title=SouNZ composer Biography: David Griffiths|url=http://sounz.org.nz/contributor/composer/1046}}</ref> Since that time he has worked as a freelance composer, operatic and recital singer and lecturer in voice, based primarily in Auckland.  He returned to the UK and Europe, after the completion of the MMus, where he was a member of various ensembles including the [[BBC Singers]].

Griffiths, on his return to New Zealand, won both of New Zealand's premier operatic competitions, the NZ Herald Aria (currently the New Zealand Aria) and the 1983 [[Mobil Song Quest]] (currently the [[Lexus Song Quest]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Tauranga Musica: Programme Schedule|url=http://www.tgamusica.co.nz/?p=4}}</ref> He has held appointments as Lecturer of Voice and Senior Lecturer at the University of Auckland through much of his career except from 1986 until 1992 where he held the same at the [[University of Otago]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Adams|first=Geoff|title=Classical Reviews|url=http://www.odt.co.nz/entertainment/music/107163/classical-reviews|newspaper=Otago Daily Times|date=22 May 2010}}</ref> and since his appointment at the University of Waikato.  He is the current convener of the Conservatorium of Music at the [[University of Waikato]], [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] and senior lecturer of voice. In 2006, Griffiths became a founding member of the [[New Zealand Chamber Soloists]] with whom he has worked in a capacity as both composer and singer.<ref>{{cite web|title=FASS:New Zealand Chamber Soloists|url=http://www.waikato.ac.nz/wfass/subjects/music/nzcs/}}</ref>

==Activities==
===Composing===
Griffiths is recognised as one of New Zealand's leading [[composer]]s and as such is fully represented by SouNZ Aotearoa, the Centre for New Zealand Music.<ref>{{cite web|title=SouNZ Aoroatea: David Griffiths|url=http://sounz.org.nz/contributor/composer/1046}}</ref>  SouNZ has on record eighty-six published works by Griffiths including choral music, song cycles, songs, opera, piano music and chamber music for a variety of instruments. He has written commissions for numerous musicians and groups including the [[Karlheinz Company]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Karlheinz Company: Performer Profile - SouNZ|url=http://sounz.org.nz/contributor/performer/1543}}</ref> and the [[New Zealand Chamber Soloists]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Big Idea: New Zealand Chamber Soloists|url=http://www.thebigidea.co.nz/profile/nz-chamber-soloists/34620}}</ref> and has received official support for compositional projects through [[Creative New Zealand]].

Griffiths has gained a particular reputation as a choral composer with choral works being performed by choirs around the world and several recordings made by choirs in the United States of America.<ref>{{cite web|title=Auckland Choral: Biography: David Griffiths|url=http://www.acs.org.nz/biographies/2011/david-griffiths.html}}</ref> The "Te Deum Laudamus" was commissioned by award winning,Seattle based vocal ensemble,<ref>{{cite web|title=About Opus 7 Seattle, USA|url=http://www.opus7.org/}}</ref> Opus 7 for their 10th anniversary celebrations in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Te Deum Laudamus: Works: Center for New Zealand Music|url=http://sounz.org.nz/works/show/16520}}</ref>  Other notable works include, "The Servant", for choir, soloist and two string quartets and operas, "The Woman from Moab", based on the biblical book of Ruth and "The White Lady".<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Waikato: Staff Profile|url=http://www.waikato.ac.nz/wfass/subjects/music/staff/david/}}</ref>

Griffiths frequently draws on existing texts for his songs.  Many of these have been of an original New Zealand setting, such as "Six Watercolours".<ref>{{cite web|title=Six Watercolours by David Griffiths: SouNZ Info|url=http://sounz.org.nz/works/show/14024}}</ref>  This work, originally commissioned by John Rimmer, consists of six art songs with poetry inspired by the paintings of Doris Lusk.  They describe some of the untouched landscapes along the New Zealand coast.  Other texts are drawn from original traditional Latin liturgical texts and a variety of sources as exhibited in the collected CD of his early art songs, "Charms and Knots".<ref>{{cite web|title=Amplifier Music: Adult contemporary: Charms & Knots|url=http://www.amplifier.co.nz/release/55688/charms-knots.html}}</ref>

===Performing===
Griffiths has performed frequently with [[New Zealand Opera]], all major choral societies in New Zealand, the [[Auckland Philharmonia Orchestra]] and the [[New Zealand Symphony Orchestra]]. He performs an extensive baritone repertoire of opera and oratorio and recital tours have taken him to the [[United Kingdom]], [[Europe]] the [[USA]] and [[Taiwan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ACS Biography on David Griffiths|url=http://www.acs.org.nz/biographies/2011/david-griffiths.html}}</ref> 

His operatic repertoire has included ''[[La Traviata]]'', ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'', ''[[The Magic Flute]]'', ''[[Tosca]]'', ''[[Gianni Schicchi]]'', ''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'', ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', ''[[Don Pasquale]]'', ''[[The Pearl Fishers]]'', ''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'', ''[[Cenerentola]]'', ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'', ''[[Julius Caesar (opera)|Julius Caesar]]'', ''[[Cos<U+00EC> fan tutte]]'', ''[[Zaida (opera)|Zaida]]'' and ''[[Galileo (opera)|Galileo]]''.  As a concert soloist, Griffiths has performed all the major works of [[J S Bach]], ''[[War Requiem]]'' by [[Benjamin Britten]], [[Elgar]]'s ''The Dream of Gerontius'', ''Elijah'' by [[Felix Mendelsohn]], ''The Light in the Wilderness'' by [[Dave Brubeck]], [[Monteverdi]]'s ''Solemn Vespers'', [[Vaughan Williams]]' ''Five Mystical Songs'', ''[[Messiah (Handel)|The Messiah]]'' by [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]] and ''[[Carmina Burana]]'' by [[Carl Orff]].<ref>{{cite web|title=FASS: David Griffiths Profile|url=http://www.waikato.ac.nz/wfass/subjects/music/staff/david/}}</ref>

Griffiths has also premiered numerous New Zealand works such as ''Orpheus in Rarohenga'' by [[John Psathas]]<ref>{{cite  web|title=Promethean Editions: Orpheus in Rorohenga - John Psathas|url=http://www.promethean-editions.com/php/WorkDetail.php?WorkID=10&Composer=John%20Psathas&ComposerID=10}}</ref> with the NZSO and performed with well known New Zealand singers such as Sir [[Donald McIntyre]], [[Malvina Major]], [[Anna Leese]] and Helen Medlyn.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eventfinder: Handel's Messiah|url=http://www.eventfinder.co.nz/2008/dec/auckland/handels-messiah}}</ref>

===Recording===
Griffiths has recorded much of the English, German and French Art Song [[repertoire]] for [[Concert FM]] as well as a significant body of New Zealand music.  CD recordings as a soloist have included works such as ''Prodigal Country'' with the New Zealand Symphony Orchestra under the direction of the late Sir [[Charles Groves]] and the ''Five Mystical Songs'' under Karen Grylls, director of the Dorian Choir<ref>{{cite web|title=ABC Classic FM: Playlist "Dorian Choir & David Griffiths" Five Mystical Songs by Vaughn Williams|url=http://www.abc.net.au/cgi-bin/common/printfriendly.pl?/classic/daily/stories/s630105.htm}}</ref> and songs by with [[David Farquhar (composer)]].

''Ahi'' a CD collaboration between the Ogen Trio and the [[New Zealand Chamber Soloists]] featured works by Griffiths and four other  leading New Zealand composers, Michael Williams, [[Gareth Farr]], Martin Lodge and [[John Psathas]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Atoll Record Catalog: Ahi 108|url=http://www.atollcd.com/catalog_detail/acd108_ahi.htm}}</ref> Griffiths has recorded CDs and DVDs for [[Naxos Records]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Naxos Person, David Griffiths|url=http://www.naxos.com/person/David_Griffiths_5181/5181.htm}}</ref> including "Missa Solemnis, Te Deum" with the New Zealand Symphony Orchestra and Tower Voices NZ[[Naxos Records]]<ref>{{cite web|title=WH Smith Entertainment: Catalog|url=http://www.whsmithentertainment.co.uk/cd/johann-nepomuk-hummel/missa-solemnis-te-deum-grodd-nz-so-tower-voices-nz/8008275.html}}</ref> as well as Kiwi Pacific Records, Herald Record Label<ref>{{cite web|title=Presto Classical - Dormi Jesu|url=http://www.prestoclassical.co.uk/w/83811/David-Griffiths-Dormi-Jesu}}</ref> and Ode Records.<ref>{{cite web|title=Presto Classical - Beata Virgo|url=http://www.prestoclassical.co.uk/w/142682/David-Griffiths-Beata-Virgo}}</ref>

===Teaching===
Griffiths has held positions of Lecturer of Voice and Senior Lecturer of voice at the [[University of Auckland]], [[University of Otago]] and [[University of Waikato]].  He is the current convener of the Conservatorium of Music, University of Waikato.<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Waikato: FASS: Staff: David Griffiths|url=http://www.waikato.ac.nz/wfass/subjects/music/staff/david/}}</ref>

